<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Colonies</emphasis>
on PDA and OA at 25 °C attaining 11-14 mm and 7-9 mm diam respectively after 7 d, white, flat, radially folded or rugose. On MEA at 25 °C, reaching 6-8 mm after 7 d, white to yellowish-white, slimy. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Hyphae</emphasis>
hyaline, septate, sometimes winding, 1.5-2.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
wide. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Sporulation</emphasis>
abundant. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Phialides</emphasis>
are mostly borne singly, curved, slightly inflated at the base, tapered at the tip, up to 38.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
long. tapering from 1.5-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
near the base to 0.5-1.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Conidia</emphasis>
cohering together on the top of phialides, one-celled, solitary, or several fascicled, ovoid or subglobose, 3.0-7.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
(x- 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
SD = 4.1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
1.18 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±">+/-</normalizedToken>
0.77, n = 50) diam. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Chlamydospores</emphasis>
and teleomorph stage were not observed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">curvum</emphasis>
. Referring to the curved Phialides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Known distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Henan Province, China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Based on the multi-locus analysis we found that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Xin Li, Y. F. Han &amp; Z. Q. Liang" authorityYear="2022" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Bionectriaceae" genus="Acremonium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Acremonium curvum" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="curvum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Acremonium curvum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had close phylogenetic affinities to other taxa of the 
<taxonomicName genus="Chrysogenum" lsidName="Chrysogenum" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Chrysogenum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-clade. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. curvum" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="curvum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">A. curvum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was similar to other taxa of the 
<taxonomicName genus="Chrysogenum" lsidName="Chrysogenum" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Chrysogenum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-clade in having simple or rarely branched conidiophores, slightly inflated at the base and tapered at tip phialides, and ovoid to subglobose conidia (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.420.4.4" author="Yang, CL" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="283 - 299" refId="B22" refString="Yang, CL, Xu, XL, Jeewon, R, Boonmee, S, Liu, YG, Hyde, KD, 2019. Acremonium arthrinii sp. nov., a mycopathogenic fungus on Arthrinium yunnanum. Phytotaxa 420 (4): 283 - 299, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.420.4.4" title="Acremonium arthrinii sp. nov., a mycopathogenic fungus on Arthrinium yunnanum." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.420.4.4" volume="420" year="2019">Yang et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Conidia of 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Hapsidospora" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hapsidospora irregularis" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="irregularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Hapsidospora irregularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. curvum" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="curvum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">A. curvum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had several fascicled at the tips of the conidiophores (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1139/b70-267" author="Malloch, D" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="1815 - 1825" refId="B12" refString="Malloch, D, Cain, RF, 1970. Five new genera in the new family Pseudeurotiaceae. Canadian Journal of Botany 48 (10): 1815 - 1825, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1139/b70-267" title="Five new genera in the new family Pseudeurotiaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.1139/b70-267" volume="48" year="1970">Malloch and Cain 1970</bibRefCitation>
). However, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. curvum" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="curvum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">A. curvum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was differentiated by having mostly curved phialides and the conidia were several fascicled at the tips of the phialides.
</paragraph>
